al life"—draws on the spirit of Hegel's Philosophy of Right and his own theory of recognition, demonstrating how concrete social spheres generate the tenets of individual freedom and a standard for what is just. Using social analysis to re-found a more grounded theory of justice, he argues that all crucial actions in Western civilization, whether in personal relationships, market-induced economic activities, or the public forum of politics, share one defining characteristic: they require the realization of a particular aspect of individual freedom. This fundamental truth informs the guiding principles of justice, enabling a wide-ranging reconsideration of its nature and application.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDemocracy. 0aLibertyxPhilosophy. 0aSocial justicexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070982708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/honn1624640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231530859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231530859/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070982-7  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles